<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="535" pageId="4" pageNumber="533" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1509,2040]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,682]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="535" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,299,1509,1535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Description:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[311,501,1510,1536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">
5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[325,340,1513,1522]" fontSize="4" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">TH</superScript>
<subScript attach="right" box="[351,493,1517,1533]" fontSize="7" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">INSTAR NYMPH</subScript>
.
</emphasis>
Body laterally compressed. 
<emphasis box="[839,915,1509,1535]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Color:</emphasis>
Mostly green in both live and dry museum specimens. 
<emphasis box="[283,378,1545,1571]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Surface:</emphasis>
Tuberculate chalazae present on the following structures: post-ocular lobes, prothorax (along anterior and dorsal margin), anteroventral margin at base of forewing pads, mesonotal and abdominal scoli, ventrolateral margins of abdominal terga, entire abdominal segment IX, and dorsoanterior and dorsoposterior margins of tibia; tuberculate chalazae varying in size, larger and prominent along the anterior surface of thoracic and abdominal scoli. Lateral surface of thorax and abdomen glabrous; elongate and slender setae covering ventral surface of body and legs, more densely distributed on ventral side of head (
<figureCitation box="[801,933,1725,1751]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Figs. 2E–H</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[950,1011,1725,1751]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Head</emphasis>
: Subtriangular; vertex bearing 8 scoli, arranged into 4 bilaterally symmetrical pairs: 2 slender scoli on upper margin, equidistant from eyes and coronal suture, curved upwards (
<figureCitation box="[432,523,1797,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
, hs1); 2 stout scoli, each at external anterior margin, juxtaposed to eyes, curved diagonally and downward (
<figureCitation box="[451,538,1833,1859]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
, hs2), fused with 2 small scoli at base, the latter directed downward (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1371,1833,1859]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
, hs4); 2 small and stout scoli at inferior margin, just below eyes, directed laterally. 
<emphasis box="[998,1079,1869,1895]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">Thorax</emphasis>
: Prothorax well developed; pair of stout scoli at base, just above head, discreetly curved, and directed upward and slightly forward (=premetopidium scoli 
<emphasis box="[212,274,1942,1967]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McKamey" box="[281,532,1941,1968]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="McKamey" pageId="4" pageNumber="533" pagination="65 - 87" refId="ref12637" refString="McKamey, S. H., Wallner, A. M. &amp; Porter, M. J. (2015) Immatures of the New World treehopper tribe Amastrini (Hemiptera, Membracidae, Smiliinae) with a key to genera. ZooKeys, 524, 65 - 87. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 524.5951" type="journal article" year="2015">
McKamey 
<emphasis box="[407,464,1941,1967]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
); tall and laterally flattened dorsoanterior projection, with 2 robust, conical scoli at apex, slightly curved laterally at tip (=postmetopidium scoli 
<emphasis box="[874,936,1978,2003]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McKamey" box="[946,1201,1977,2004]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="McKamey" pageId="4" pageNumber="533" pagination="65 - 87" refId="ref12637" refString="McKamey, S. H., Wallner, A. M. &amp; Porter, M. J. (2015) Immatures of the New World treehopper tribe Amastrini (Hemiptera, Membracidae, Smiliinae) with a key to genera. ZooKeys, 524, 65 - 87. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 524.5951" type="journal article" year="2015">
McKamey 
<emphasis box="[1073,1131,1977,2003]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="533">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
); suprahumeral buds relatively inconspicuous, consisting of small lateral protuberance well above eyes; posterior process triangular, reaching anterior margin of metanotum, resting under mesonotal scoli. Mesonotum with pair of large scoli, curved forward apically, enclosing tip of posterior process. Metanotum with pair of small scoli, leaning forward against mesonotum. Forewing pads emarginate ventrally, sheltering metathoracic legs in repose, venation barely perceptible (except tinged bright green in live specimens); wing pads reaching fourth abdominal segment; hind wing pads subtriangular, attaining apex of forewing pads, anal margin mostly exposed (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1172,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Figs. 2D, F, H</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[1191,1297,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Abdominal terga III–VIII with pair of stout and enlarged dorsal scoli, each pair slightly arched forward (except for scoli in segment VIII, curved backward) and fused basally. Segment IX tubular, elongate (more than half the length of rest of abdomen), bearing one pair of apical spine-like scoli, directed posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[1019,1181,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[163,1423,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hyphinoe obliqua (Walker, 1858). Adult: A) Frontal view, B) lateral view, C) dorsal view. Last instar exuvia: D) dorsal view, E) frontal view, F) lateral view, G) close-up frontal view, H) frontolateral view. as: abdominal scoli; hs: head scoli; mss: mesothoracic scoli; mts: metathoracic scoli; pms: premetopidium scoli; pos: postmetopidium scoli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577281/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Figs. 2D, F, H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
